[5] South Korea - WHO 1 Jun 2015
Date: 1 Jun 2015
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response Network, Disease Outbreak News [edited]
http://who.int/csr/don/01-june-2015-mers-korea/en/


Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) - Republic of Korea 1 Jun 2015
-----------------------------------
On 31 May 2015, the National IHR Focal Point of the Republic of Korea notified WHO of 2 additional confirmed cases of Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (MERS-CoV).

Details of the cases are as follows:

1- The case is a 35-year-old male who developed symptoms of cough, sputum and fever on 6 May [2015] and was admitted to hospital on 13 May [2015]. The patient has been on tuberculosis medication since his son was diagnosed with the bacterial disease in April [2015]. Between [15 and 17 May 2015], he shared the same ward with the 1st case during his hospitalization from 15 to 17 May [2015]. On 20 May [2015], after his discharge, the patient visited 2 different hospitals due to fever and was put on antibiotics. As symptoms persisted despite antibiotic therapy, he was admitted to a hospital again on 27 May [2015] and confirmed positive for MERS-CoV on 29 May [2015].

2- The case is a 35-year-old male whose mother shared the same ward with the 1st case. From 15 to 21 May [2015], the patient visited his mother every day at the hospital. He developed symptoms and visited an emergency room on 24 May [2015]. The patient was admitted to hospital between 25 and 27 May [2015] and confirmed positive for MERS-CoV on 30 May [2015].

Contact tracing of household contacts and healthcare contacts is ongoing for the cases.

Globally, WHO has been notified of 1154 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 431 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

[Earlier reports by WHO had mentioned 427 deaths; this has been corrected to be 431 deaths. - Mod.MPP]

******
[6] Saudi Arabia - WHO 1 Jun 2015
Date: 1 Jun 2015
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response Network, Disease Outbreak News [edited]
http://who.int/csr/don/01-june-2015-mers-saudi-arabia/en/


Middle East Respiratory Syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) - Saudi Arabia 1 Jun 2015

Between 24 and 25 May 2015, the National IHR Focal Point for the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia notified WHO of 2 additional cases of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) infection, including 1 death.

Details of the cases are as follows:

1- A 71-year-old, non-national male from Hofuf city developed symptoms on 21 May [2015] while admitted to hospital since 10 May [2015] due to an unrelated medical condition. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on 24 May [2015]. Investigation of history of exposure to the known risk factors in the 14 days prior to the onset of symptoms is ongoing. Currently, the patient is in stable condition in a negative pressure isolation room on a ward.

2- A 68-year-old female from Hofuf city was admitted to a cardiac centre on 13 May [2015] complaining of chest pain and fever. On 20 May [2015], while hospitalized, the patient developed shortness of breath. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 23 May 2015 and passed away on 25 May [2015]. The patient had comorbidities. Her family owns sheep and camels. An investigation of history of exposure to these animals and to other known risk factors in the 14 days prior to onset of symptoms is ongoing.

Contact tracing of household contacts and healthcare contacts is ongoing for these cases.

The National IHR Focal Point for the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia also notified WHO of the death of 2 previously reported MERS-CoV cases. The cases were reported in previous DONs on 25 May [2015] (case n. 1) and on 17 May [2015] (case n. 1).

Globally, WHO has been notified of 1152 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 434 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

******
[7] Qatar - WHO 31 May 2015
Date: 31 May 2015
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response Network, Disease Outbreak News [edited]
http://who.int/csr/don/31-may-2015-mers-qatar/en/


Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) - Qatar 31 May 2015
--------------------------------------
On 22 May 2015, the National IHR Focal Point of Qatar notified WHO of 1 additional case of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) infection.

Details of the case are as follows:

A 73-year-old male from Doha city developed symptoms on 10 May [2015] and sought medical care at a hospital, whereupon he was treated symptomatically and sent home on the same day. On 12 May [2015], as symptoms worsened, the patient was admitted to the same hospital. On 21 May [2015], he tested positive for MERS-CoV. The patient has comorbidities. He has no history of direct contact with camels; however, his family owns a camel barn, and family members have a history of contact with camels and consumption of raw camel milk. The patient has no history of exposure to other known risk factors in the 14 days prior to onset of symptoms. Currently, the patient is in critical condition in ICU. Contact tracing of household contacts and healthcare contacts is ongoing for the case.

Globally, WHO has been notified of 1150 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 427 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

[The HealthMap/ProMED map of Qatar can be found at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3402059,130.

According to the WHO reports, there have now been a total of 1154 cases of MERS-CoV infection including at least 431 related deaths confirmed and reported to WHO since 2012 (if one reads the WHO updates in reverse order of presentation above (sections [7] [6] and [5], the global tally of MERS-CoV cases increases in keeping with each of the reports so the final most recent tally is that presented in section [5] of 1154 cases including at least 431 deaths). The WHO updates provided above in this update include cases recently confirmed in South Korea, Saudi Arabia and Qatar (see MERS-CoV (52): Oman, Saudi Arabia, South Korea, WHO, RFI 20150531.3399248, MERS-CoV (51): South Korea, Saudi Arabia, new cases, RFI 20150530.3397494, MERS-CoV (50): South Korea, China ex South Korea conf. Saudi Arabia 20150529.3395374, MERS-CoV (49): South Korea, China ex South Korea susp, Saudi Arabia, Qatar 20150528.3393353, MERS-CoV (47): South Korea, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, Qatar, WHO 20150526.3383778, MERS-CoV (46): Qatar, Saudi Arabia, RFI 20150523.3381072, MERS-CoV (45): Saudi Arabia, South Korea, RFI 20150522.3378310 for initial reports on these cases). Of note is that of the 5 cases confirmed by WHO in the above updates (2 in South Korea, 2 in Saudi Arabia and 1 in Qatar), 4 of the cases involved nosocomial transmission, and one may have been indirect exposure to MERS-CoV infected camels, all cases where "high risk" exposures have been identified. - Mod.MPP]
